Hypothesis testing on A/B tests¶

Research purpose¶

Identify hypotheses that will help increase the revenue of the online store.

Research description¶

Prepare a list of hypotheses to increase revenue of a large online store. Prioritize hypotheses, run an A/B test and analyze the results.

Data description¶

hypothesis.csv structure
Hypothesis a brief description of the hypothesis;
Reach user coverage on a 10-point scale;
Impact impact on users on a 10-point scale;
Confidence confidence in the hypothesis on a 10-point scale;
Efforts the cost of resources to test the hypothesis on a 10-point scale. The greater the value of Efforts, the more expensive hypothesis testing is.

Orders.csv structure
TransactionID order ID;
visitorID ID of the user who made the order;
date the date when the order was made; revenue order revenue;
group the A/B test group that the order fell into.

Visitors.csv structure
date date;
group A/B test group;
visitors the number of users on the specified date in the specified A/B test group

Data preprocessing¶

In [3]:
def first_look (df):
    print('------------- First 5 lines ------------')
    display(df.sample(5))
    print('------------- Data types ------------')
    display(df.info())
    print('------------- Gaps ------------')
    for element in df.columns:
        if df[element].isna().any().mean() > 0:
            print(element, '-', df[element].isna().sum())
        else:
            print(element, '- None')
    print('------------- Duplicates ------------')
    if df.duplicated().sum() > 0:
        print(df.duplicated().sum())
    else:
        print('No Duplicates')

Prioritization of hypotheses by the ICE framework. Sort them in descending order of priority¶

ICE (confidence, effort, reach):
$$ICE = \frac{Impact * Confidence}{Efforts}$$

In [6]:
hypothesis['ice'] = round((hypothesis['impact'] * hypothesis['confidence'])/hypothesis['efforts'], 2)
display(hypothesis.sort_values(by='ice', ascending=False).head(5))
hypothesis reach impact confidence efforts ice
8 , ... 1 9 9 5 16.20
0 ,... 3 10 8 6 13.33
7 ... 10 7 8 5 11.20
6 ... 5 3 8 3 8.00
2 ... 8 3 7 3 7.00

Prioritization of hypotheses by the RICE framework. Sort them in descending order of priority¶

RICE (influence, confidence, effort, reach):
$$RICE = \frac{Rearch * Impact * Confidence}{Efforts}$$

In [7]:
hypothesis['rice'] = round((hypothesis['reach'] * hypothesis['impact'] * hypothesis['confidence'])/hypothesis['efforts'], 2)
display(hypothesis.sort_values(by='rice', ascending=False).head(5))
hypothesis reach impact confidence efforts ice rice
7 ... 10 7 8 5 11.20 112.0
2 ... 8 3 7 3 7.00 56.0
0 ,... 3 10 8 6 13.33 40.0
6 ... 5 3 8 3 8.00 40.0
8 , ... 1 9 9 5 16.20 16.2
In [8]:
y = hypothesis['ice'] 
z = hypothesis['rice'] 
n = hypothesis.index 

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.scatter(z, y)

for i, txt in enumerate(n):
    ax.annotate(txt, (z[i], y[i]), size=20)

plt.title("Prioritizing hypotheses with ICE and RICE") 
plt.xlabel("RICE") 
plt.ylabel("ICE")
fig.set_figheight(7)
fig.set_figwidth(7) 

plt.show();

The prioritization of hypotheses when using RICE instead of ICE has changed due to the inclusion of an additional evaluation factor Reach - audience reach.
Thus, the priority of the hypothesis can be very high, but in a narrow group of users. That on the scale of all recipients of the hypothesis will be insignificant.
The introduction of the Reach criterion, meaning influence, coverage, increases the reliability of the assessment of the priority of the hypothesis.

Cumulative revenue graph by group¶

In [18]:
# creating an array of unique pairs of date values and test groups
datesGroups = orders[['date','group']].drop_duplicates() 

ordersAggregated = datesGroups.apply(lambda x: orders[np.logical_and(orders['date'] <= x['date'], 
                                                                     orders['group'] == x['group'])]\
.agg({'date' : 'max', 
      'group' : 'max', 
      'transactionId' : 'nunique', 
      'visitorId' : 'nunique', 
      'revenue' : 'sum'}), axis=1).sort_values(by=['date','group']) 

visitorsAggregated = datesGroups.apply(lambda x: visitors[np.logical_and(visitors['date'] <= x['date'], 
                                                                         visitors['group'] == x['group'])]\
                                       .agg({'date' : 'max', 
                                             'group' : 'max', 
                                             'visitors' : 'sum'}), axis=1).sort_values(by=['date','group'])

# we combine cumulative data in one table and assign understandable names to its columns
cumulativeData = ordersAggregated.merge(visitorsAggregated, left_on=['date', 'group'], right_on=['date', 'group'])
cumulativeData.columns = ['date', 'group', 'orders', 'buyers', 'revenue', 'visitors']

The schedules of both groups are growing, which means that revenue increases over time.
A sharp jump in Group B's revenue around 08/18/2019 indicates a sharp jump in the number of orders or the cost of orders.

Graph of the cumulative average check by group¶

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))

plt.legend()

plt.ylabel("Average bill, c.u.")
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

On the chart of the average check for group B, there is also a jump in the area of 18.08.2019.
This suggests that the reason for this jump is in the cost of orders.
Further, the chart shows a downward trend and tries to stabilize after the jump. So we should continue the experiment until the stabilization of group B.
The average receipt of group A also had several peaks and falls, but judging by the revenue schedule, they were compensated by the number of orders and by the end of the experiment, the schedule of group A stabilized.

Hypothesis check of conversion difference between groups on "raw" data¶

Calculation of the statistical significance of differences in conversion between groups based on "raw" data without removing abnormal users.
Null hypothesis
H0: There are no differences in conversion between the groups.
Alternative hypothesis
H1: there are differences in conversion between groups

In [30]:
visitorsADaily = visitors[visitors['group'] == 'A'][['date', 'visitors']]
visitorsADaily.columns = ['date', 'visitorsPerDateA']

visitorsBDaily = visitors[visitors['group'] == 'B'][['date', 'visitors']]
visitorsBDaily.columns = ['date', 'visitorsPerDateB']

visitorsACummulative = visitorsADaily.apply(
    lambda x: visitorsADaily[visitorsADaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'visitorsPerDateA': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
)
visitorsACummulative.columns = ['date', 'visitorsCummulativeA']

visitorsBCummulative = visitorsBDaily.apply(
    lambda x: visitorsBDaily[visitorsBDaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'visitorsPerDateB': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
)
visitorsBCummulative.columns = ['date', 'visitorsCummulativeB']

ordersADaily = (
    orders[orders['group'] == 'A'][['date', 'transactionId', 'visitorId', 'revenue']]
    .groupby('date', as_index=False)
    .agg({'transactionId': pd.Series.nunique, 'revenue': 'sum'})
)
ordersADaily.columns = ['date', 'ordersPerDateA', 'revenuePerDateA']

ordersBDaily = (
    orders[orders['group'] == 'B'][['date', 'transactionId', 'visitorId', 'revenue']]
    .groupby('date', as_index=False)
    .agg({'transactionId': pd.Series.nunique, 'revenue': 'sum'})
)
ordersBDaily.columns = ['date', 'ordersPerDateB', 'revenuePerDateB']

ordersACummulative = ordersADaily.apply(
    lambda x: ordersADaily[ordersADaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'ordersPerDateA': 'sum', 'revenuePerDateA': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
).sort_values(by=['date'])
ordersACummulative.columns = [
    'date',
    'ordersCummulativeA',
    'revenueCummulativeA',
]

ordersBCummulative = ordersBDaily.apply(
    lambda x: ordersBDaily[ordersBDaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'ordersPerDateB': 'sum', 'revenuePerDateB': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
).sort_values(by=['date'])
ordersBCummulative.columns = [
    'date',
    'ordersCummulativeB',
    'revenueCummulativeB',
]

data = (
    ordersADaily.merge(
        ordersBDaily, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left'
    )
    .merge(ordersACummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(ordersBCummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsADaily, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsBDaily, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsACummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsBCummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
)
data['conversionA'] = data['ordersPerDateA']/data['visitorsPerDateA']
data['conversionB'] = data['ordersPerDateB']/data['visitorsPerDateB']
data['conversionCummulativeA'] = data['ordersCummulativeA']/data['visitorsCummulativeA']
data['conversionCummulativeB'] = data['ordersCummulativeB']/data['visitorsCummulativeB']
display(data.head(5))

Interim summary¶

Hypothesis check of conversion between groups on "cleared" data¶

The 95th and 99th percentiles of the average checks found in p.5.9 are equal to 28,000 and 58,233 rubles.
And the 95th and 99th percentiles of the number of orders per user are 2 and 4 orders per user.

We will take for abnormal users those who have made at least 2 orders or made an order more expensive than 30,000 rubles.
So we will remove 5% of users with the largest number of orders and from 1% to 5% of users with expensive orders.
Let's make slices of users with more than 4 orders usersWithManyOrders and users who have made orders more than 30,000 usersWithExpensiveOrders.
Let's combine them in the abnormal Users table.

visitorsADaily = visitors[visitors['group'] == 'A'][['date', 'visitors']]
visitorsADaily.columns = ['date', 'visitorsPerDateA']

visitorsBDaily = visitors[visitors['group'] == 'B'][['date', 'visitors']]
visitorsBDaily.columns = ['date', 'visitorsPerDateB']

visitorsACummulative = visitorsADaily.apply(
    lambda x: visitorsADaily[visitorsADaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'visitorsPerDateA': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
)
visitorsACummulative.columns = ['date', 'visitorsCummulativeA']

visitorsBCummulative = visitorsBDaily.apply(
    lambda x: visitorsBDaily[visitorsBDaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'visitorsPerDateB': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
)
visitorsBCummulative.columns = ['date', 'visitorsCummulativeB']

ordersADaily = (
    orders[orders['group'] == 'A'][['date', 'transactionId', 'visitorId', 'revenue']]
    .groupby('date', as_index=False)
    .agg({'transactionId': pd.Series.nunique, 'revenue': 'sum'})
)
ordersADaily.columns = ['date', 'ordersPerDateA', 'revenuePerDateA']

ordersBDaily = (
    orders[orders['group'] == 'B'][['date', 'transactionId', 'visitorId', 'revenue']]
    .groupby('date', as_index=False)
    .agg({'transactionId': pd.Series.nunique, 'revenue': 'sum'})
)
ordersBDaily.columns = ['date', 'ordersPerDateB', 'revenuePerDateB']

ordersACummulative = ordersADaily.apply(
    lambda x: ordersADaily[ordersADaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'ordersPerDateA': 'sum', 'revenuePerDateA': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
).sort_values(by=['date'])
ordersACummulative.columns = [
    'date',
    'ordersCummulativeA',
    'revenueCummulativeA',
]

ordersBCummulative = ordersBDaily.apply(
    lambda x: ordersBDaily[ordersBDaily['date'] <= x['date']].agg(
        {'date': 'max', 'ordersPerDateB': 'sum', 'revenuePerDateB': 'sum'}
    ),
    axis=1,
).sort_values(by=['date'])
ordersBCummulative.columns = [
    'date',
    'ordersCummulativeB',
    'revenueCummulativeB',
]

dataClean = (
    ordersADaily.merge(
        ordersBDaily, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left'
    )
    .merge(ordersACummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(ordersBCummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsADaily, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsBDaily, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsACummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
    .merge(visitorsBCummulative, left_on='date', right_on='date', how='left')
)
dataClean['conversionA'] = dataClean['ordersPerDateA']/dataClean['visitorsPerDateA']
dataClean['conversionB'] = dataClean['ordersPerDateB']/dataClean['visitorsPerDateB']

Project summary¶

Based on the analysis of both "raw" and anomaly-free A/B test results, the following conclusions can be drawn:

  • There is a difference in conversion between groups
    • A higher conversion rate is shown by the group In
  • There is no statistically significant difference in the average check between the groups
  • There are differences in the average number of orders per user between groups
  • More orders per user in group B

Due to the fact that

  • revenue, average receipt and conversion charts have stabilized by the end of the test
  • clearing the data did not affect the acceptance of hypotheses
  • the graph of the difference in conversion between groups confirms that the conversion of group B is consistently better than the group
  • the graph of the difference in the average check indicates that the results of group B are steadily improving.

From the above, we can conclude that the test should be stopped.
Significant differences between the groups in terms of conversion were revealed - group B has a higher conversion rate.
There is no statistically significant difference in the average check between the groups.
